There is also a "**for range-based loop**", which is used exclusively to loop through elements in an array.

      syntax -   for index, value:= range collection {
                    // Loop body
                 }


                 arr := [3]int{1, 2, 3}
                 for index, value := range arr {
                    fmt.Println(index, value)
                 }
- index: Optional variable that holds the index (or key, for maps) of the current element in the collection.
- value: Variable that holds the value of the current element in the collection.
- collection: The array, slice, map, string, or channel over which the loop iterates.

### Task
Write a program that does the following
- Create an integer array $num$ which has the integers - 10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80
- Output to the console the following
  - All the elements of the given array in separate lines
  - Use the "**for range-based loop**" loop syntax defined above

